## Purpose

Rules and conventions for creating Item Tile components and their variants. Item Tiles are compact product cards used in 2×2 category grids within horizontally scrollable carousels. They display a product image, badge, heart/favorite toggle, price, and product name.

---

## Component Location

```
client/components/walmart/WCPItemTile.tsx       # Component
client/components/walmart/WCPItemTile.module.css # Styles
```

**Import**:
```tsx
import { WCPItemTile, WCPItemTileProps, ItemTileBadgeType } from '@/components/walmart/WCPItemTile';
```

---

## HARD RULES (No Exceptions)

### 1. Always Use WCPItemTile — Never Build Custom Product Tiles

- **ALWAYS** use `WCPItemTile` for any compact product tile in a grid or carousel
- **NEVER** create a one-off product tile with inline styles or a local component
- **NEVER** duplicate the price layout logic — it lives in `WCPItemTile` only

```tsx
// ❌ WRONG — custom product tile
<div className="myTile">
  <img src={product.image} />
  <span>${product.price}.{product.cents}</span>
  <p>{product.name}</p>
</div>

// ✅ CORRECT — use the standard component
<WCPItemTile
  image={product.image}
  name={product.name}
  price="24"
  cents="88"
  badge={{ label: 'Best seller', type: 'bestseller' }}
/>
```

### 2. Badge Types — Use Only the Defined Set

Four badge types are supported. Each maps to a specific `WCPFlag` variant:

| `ItemTileBadgeType` | WCPFlag variant | Visual |
|---|---|---|
| `'bestseller'` | `savings-bold` | Solid red |
| `'deal'` | `savings-subtle` | Light red tint |
| `'popular'` | `confidence-subtle` | Light blue tint |
| `'rollback'` | `holiday-restricted` | Dark charcoal |

- **NEVER** invent new badge types without adding them to the `ItemTileBadgeType` union and `BADGE_VARIANT_MAP`
- **NEVER** pass raw `WCPFlagVariant` strings — always use the `badge` prop with `{ label, type }`

### 3. Price Layout — Two Variants Only

**Default price** (black text):
```tsx
<WCPItemTile price="98" cents="00" />
// Renders: $98⁰⁰
```

**Savings price** (green text with "Now" prefix):
```tsx
<WCPItemTile
  price="169"
  cents="98"
  pricePrefix="Now"
  originalPrice="$200.00"
  priceSuffix="/mo"
/>
// Renders: Now $169⁹⁸/mo  (green)
//          $200.00          (strikethrough)
```

**Rules**:
- `pricePrefix` triggers the green savings style — when present, all price elements turn green
- `originalPrice` renders as a strikethrough line below the price row
- `priceSuffix` (e.g. "/mo") renders at the baseline of the price
- Dollar sign and cents are superscript (14px) relative to the main price (24px)
- **NEVER** hardcode price colors — the `.priceRowSavings` class handles the green color via `var(--ld-semantic-color-text-positive)`

### 4. Heart / Favorite Toggle

- **ALWAYS** use `WCPHeartView` with `size="small"` inside item tiles
- **ALWAYS** use `calloutPosition="top"` so the tooltip appears above the heart (not clipped by adjacent tiles)
- The heart is positioned at `top: 20px; right: 4px` on the tile (below the flag badge)
- Heart `z-index: 4` is higher than flag `z-index: 2` so the callout is never covered

```tsx
// ✅ CORRECT — inside WCPItemTile (already wired)
<WCPHeartView size="small" calloutPosition="top" />

// ❌ WRONG — wrong size or position for item tiles
<WCPHeartView size="medium" calloutPosition="left" />
```

### 5. Image Requirements

- Image area is fixed at `145px` height with `object-fit: contain`
- Images should be product photos on white/transparent backgrounds
- Use CDN URLs from `PRODUCT_IMAGES` constant — never `placeholder.com` or `picsum.photos`
- **NEVER** use images with baked-in UI elements (hearts, badges, shadows)

### 6. Consistent Tile Sizing

- Tiles MUST use `height: 100%` to fill their grid cell
- The body section uses `flex: 1; min-height: 72px` to ensure uniform height
- The parent grid MUST use `grid-auto-rows: 1fr` so all tiles in a row match height
- **NEVER** set a fixed pixel height on the tile — let the grid equalize them

```css
/* ✅ CORRECT — parent grid */
.productGrid {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
  grid-auto-rows: 1fr;
  gap: 8px;
}
```

